06429nam a22010095i 9783110690149DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021943692  a97831106901497 a10.1515/97831106901492doi  a(DE-B1597)542115  a(OCoLC)1269268935  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aKJC5515b.W45 2021 4aJV4011b.W45 2021 (Online) 7aHIS0370302bisacsh04a988.012231 aWeiske, Constanze, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLawful Conquest? :bEuropean Colonial Law and Appropriation Practices in Northeastern South America, Trinidad, and Tobago, 1498–1817 /cConstanze Weiske. 1aMünchen ;aWien : bDe Gruyter Oldenbourg, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (XI, 343 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDialectics of the Global ,x2570-2289 ;v1200tFrontmatter -- tOn the Series -- tAcknowledgements -- tContents -- tChapter 1 Introduction -- tChapter 2 European Colonial Law and Appropriation Practices in the Americas -- tChapter 3 Spanish De Jure Myths (1493–1573) -- tChapter 4 Spanish Colonial Appropriation Practices in Terra Firme and Trinidad (1503–1591) -- tChapter 5 San Joseph de Oruña (1592–1802) -- tChapter 6 Santo Tome (1595–1699) -- tChapter 7 Violent Capuchin Removal and Spatial Extensions (1682–1817) -- tChapter 8 Dutch De Jure Myths (1581–1764) -- tChapter 9 Dutch Appropriation Practices on the Wild Coast and Tobago (1581–1673) -- tChapter 10 Essequibo and the Limits of Plantations (1670/75–1803) -- tChapter 11 Dutch Inland Posts and the Limits of Jurisdiction and Interference (1737–1790) -- tChapter 12 Dutch Posts on the “Wild Coast” and the Limits of Alliance (1678–1814) -- tChapter 13 Conclusion -- tList of Abbreviations -- tList of Figures -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe global expansion of European colonization is commonly perceived as lawful according to the valid European colonial law of the time. This book is substantially challenging this belief by uncovering its legal justifications based on discovery and terra nullius as retrospectively created legal fictions and demonstrating it´s untenability in practice. Focused on the critical reconstruction of Spanish and Dutch colonization practices in northeastern South America, Trinidad and Tobago between 1498 and 1817, the book offers an illuminating view on the European shadow of the colonial past in the Americas. Based on the application of an innovative comparative spatio-legal Global History approach to 1,770 excavated European colonial written sources from archives of both sides of the Atlantic in comparison to the colonial legal provisions of Europe´s most influential legal writers, the book, moreover, provides a substantial argument to the contemporary Caribbean-European reparation debate in favor of the return of Indigenous Peoples´ historical territories. Therefore, the book calls for the extension of the traditional territory approach to reparations of the United Nations Declaration of the Rights of Indigenous Peoples (UNDRIPs) and the Inter-American Court of Human Rights (IACHR).  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aConquest, Right of. 0aDoctrine of discovery (International law) 0aDoctrine of discovery (International law). 0aIndians of South AmericaxLegal status, laws, etc. 0aLand settlementxLaw and legislationzNetherlandsxHistory. 0aLand settlementxLaw and legislationzSpainxHistory. 0aLawzNetherlandsxColonies. 0aLawzSpainxColonies. 0aRes nullius. 4aDeclaration on the Rights of Indigenous Peoples. 4aDekolonisation. 4aKolonisation. 4aTrinidad und Tobago. 7aHISTORY / Modern / General.2bisacsh  